Uncombable hair syndrome (UHS) may first become apparent any time between the ages of 3 months and 12 years.[10661] It only affects the scalp hair. The quantity of  hair remains normal, but the hair often grows slowly.[702] Over time the hair becomes progressively silvery-blond or straw-colored; dry and disordered (standing out and growing in different directions); and unmanageable to comb flat.[10661] In some cases, constant efforts to groom the hair&nbsp;lead to breakage, but increased&nbsp;fragility is not a constant feature of the condition. In later childhood, there is usually a considerable amount of&nbsp;spontaneous improvement.[700][10665]<br />
<br />
In cases where UHS is part of a syndrome, there may be other signs and symptoms present; therefore, it is important to determine whether the UHS is isolated or syndromic.&nbsp;
